WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:31.310 --> 00:02:50.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of Congress in Washington,
D.C.

00:02:50.630 --> 00:03:08.049
[ Silence ]

00:03:08.049 --> 00:03:42.880
[ Background Conversation ]

00:03:42.880 --> 00:04:22.680
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: It's so wonderful to see
so many people here on Friday night for a

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:28.670
fabulous lecture. That's so great [laughing].
Anyway, welcome. I'm Betsy Peterson. I am

00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:33.660
the Director of the American Folklife Center
here at the Library of Congress. And I want

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:40.730
to welcome you to a very special edition of
our Benjamin Botkin Folklife Lecture Series.

00:04:40.730 --> 00:04:46.890
Now, for those of you we don't know what that's
all about, the American Folklife Center was

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:55.630
founded in 1976 by Congress with a mandate
to preserve and present American folklife.

00:04:55.630 --> 00:05:03.580
And we were placed here at the Library very
specifically. Congress chose the Library of

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:10.580
Congress as the site because the Library already
had an incredibly vast archive of traditional

00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:16.419
music and culture. And so it seemed like the
best place to be. And it's an archive that

00:05:16.419 --> 00:05:23.590
has been built for decades by the likes of
John and Alan Lomax and Benjamin Botkin. And,

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:31.440
actually, the archives plays a role and influences
the topic that Billy Bragg is going to be

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:37.240
talking about tonight. And we'll be finding
out more about that. The Benjamin Botkin Lecture

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:43.470
Series, which is named after one of those
distinguished folklorists, provides a platform

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:52.900
for professional -- I'm sorry -- professional
academic individuals, people from the public

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:59.150
sector, from the university, as well as colleagues
working independently in folklore at their

00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:05.819
musicology, cultural heritage, and related
fields to share their findings in their ongoing

00:06:05.819 --> 00:06:10.490
research. Now, that's great for the public.
I think that's great for you. And it's certainly

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:16.990
great for us here at the Center because these
lectures form an important part of our accusations

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:24.030
as well. And each one is recorded and becomes
a part of the permanent archive -- I mean

00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:29.160
-- yes, part of the permanent archive here
at the Library so that future generations

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:37.410
can enjoy, listen, and study. So, that reminds
me of my last caveat for you all, which is

00:06:37.410 --> 00:06:43.990
that this is a good time to say, if you have
a cell phone or a mobile device, please turn

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:50.919
it off or you will be memorialized in our
archive [laughter]. So this evening we have

00:06:50.919 --> 00:06:58.470
a very special honor to present a Botkin lecture
who falls -- of -- a Botkin lecturer -- excuse

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:05.301
me -- who falls outside of the usual categories
of academic or public sector research. And

00:07:05.301 --> 00:07:14.419
so to introduce Billy Bragg and his work,
please welcome our own Steve Winick. Thanks.

00:07:14.419 --> 00:07:16.180
[ Applause ]

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:22.850
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Thank you. As Betsy mentioned,
I'm Steve Winick. I'm the Editor here at the

00:07:22.850 --> 00:07:26.350
American Folklife Center at the Library of
Congress. And I should say that this event

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:30.139
is also cosponsored by the Folklore Society
of Greater Washington so we want to thank

00:07:30.139 --> 00:07:34.759
FSGD for cosponsoring this with is. And I
should also say that I'm pretty thrilled to

00:07:34.759 --> 00:07:39.620
have such a distinguished speaker. When I
was a teenager, I confess, that I was a big

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:44.659
Billy Bragg fan. And he's one of the first
artists whose work I got as it came out as

00:07:44.659 --> 00:07:49.460
opposed to years after it came out because
I was just old enough in the 1980s to have

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:54.289
money and to have friends who were cool. And
that's a big theme in Billy's book as well,

00:07:54.289 --> 00:07:59.340
the importance of teenagers in the music scene.
So, like many people, my musical tastes kind

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:03.530
of changed over the years and I ended up involved
